To add a loading animation to your login page in React, you can follow these steps:

1. Firstly, install a package for loading animation. For this example, we will use react-spinners.

```bash
npm install react-spinners --save
```

2. Import the package and create a state variable `loading` with a default value of `false` in your login component.

```js
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { css } from '@emotion/react';
import ClipLoader from 'react-spinners/ClipLoader';

function LoginPage() {
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  // ...
}
```

3. Create a function to handle the login process. This function will set the `loading` state to `true` before making the API request, and then set it back to `false` after receiving the response.

```js
async function handleLogin(e) {
  e.preventDefault();
  setLoading(true);

  // Your login process here, e.g., making the API request
  // ...

  setLoading(false);
}
```

4. In your JSX, use a conditional rendering to show the loading animation when the state `loading` is set to `true`. You can add this to your form or inside the button, depending on the desired design.

```js
{/* ... */}

<form onSubmit={handleLogin}>
  {/* Your form fields go here... */}

  <button type="submit">
    {loading ? (
      <ClipLoader color="#ffffff" loading={loading} css={spinnerCSS} size={20} />
    ) : (
      "Login"
    )}
  </button>
</form>

{/* ... */}
```

5. You can customize the loading animation by adding some basic CSS:

```js
const spinnerCSS = css`
  display: inline-block;
  margin-left: 8px;
`;
```

Now, the loading animation will be shown when the user submits the form, and it will disappear when the response is received.

In this example, I will demonstrate how to implement JSON Web Tokens (JWT) to authenticate users in a React app with a C# backend using ASP.NET Core Web API.

**Backend (C# )**

First, create a new ASP.NET Core Web API project in Visual Studio or using dotnet CLI. Then, install the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` NuGet package.

1. Set up JWT authentication in the `Startup.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer;
using Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens;

public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    //...
    // Add JWT authentication
    var key = Encoding.ASCII.GetBytes("your_secret_key"); // Use a secret key here
    services.AddAuthentication(x =>
    {
        x.DefaultAuthenticateScheme = JwtBearerDefaults.AuthenticationScheme;
        x.DefaultChallengeScheme = JwtBearerDefaults.AuthenticationScheme;
    })
    .AddJwtBearer(x =>
    {
        x.RequireHttpsMetadata = false;
        x.SaveToken = true;
        x.TokenValidationParameters = new TokenValidationParameters
        {
            ValidateIssuerSigningKey = true,
            IssuerSigningKey = new SymmetricSecurityKey(key),
            ValidateIssuer = false,
            ValidateAudience = false
        };
    });
    //...
}

public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
{
    //...
    app.UseAuthentication(); // Add authentication middleware
    app.UseAuthorization(); 
    //...
}
```

2. Implement login functionality in your controller:

```csharp
using System.IdentityModel.Tokens.Jwt;
using Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens;
using System.Security.Claims;

[ApiController]
[Route("api/[controller]")]
public class AuthController : ControllerBase
{
    [HttpPost("login")]
    public IActionResult Login([FromBody] LoginRequest request)
    {
        // Validate the user's credentials (replace with your own logic)
        if (IsValidUser(request.Username, request.Password))
        {
            var tokenHandler = new JwtSecurityTokenHandler();
            var key = Encoding.ASCII.GetBytes("your_secret_key");
            var tokenDescriptor = new SecurityTokenDescriptor
            {
                Subject = new ClaimsIdentity(new Claim[]
                {
                    new Claim(ClaimTypes.Name, request.Username),
                    new Claim(ClaimTypes.Role, "Student"), // Set the role of the user
                }),
                Expires = DateTime.UtcNow.AddDays(7),
                SigningCredentials = new SigningCredentials(new SymmetricSecurityKey(key), SecurityAlgorithms.HmacSha256Signature)
            };
            var token = tokenHandler.CreateToken(tokenDescriptor);
            var user = new
            {
                username = request.Username,
                role = "Student", // This should correspond to the role in Claims
                token = tokenHandler.WriteToken(token)
            };
            return Ok(user);
        }
        else
        {
            return Unauthorized();
        }
    }

    private bool IsValidUser(string username, string password)
    {
        // Replace this with your own logic to validate the user's credentials
        return username == "testuser" && password == "testpassword";
    }
}
```

**Frontend (React)**

Now, let's implement the login functionality in your React app.

1. Install `axios` to make HTTP requests:

```sh
npm install axios
```

2. Create a login form and handle a login request:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import axios from 'axios';

function LoginForm() {
  const [username, setUsername] = useState('');
  const [password, setPassword] = useState('');

  const handleLogin = async (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    try {
      const response = await axios.post('https://your-api-url/api/auth/login', {
        username,
        password,
      });

      localStorage.setItem('user', JSON.stringify(response.data));
    } catch (error) {
      console.log('Login error:', error);
    }
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleLogin}>
      <label>
        Username:
        <input
          type="text"
          value={username}
          onChange={(e) => setUsername(e.target.value)}
        />
      </label>
      <br />
      <label>
        Password:
        <input
          type="password"
          value={password}
          onChange={(e) => setPassword(e.target.value)}
        />
      </label>
      <br />
      <input type="submit" value="Login" />
    </form>
  );
}

export default LoginForm;
```

When the user logs in, their token and other user data will be stored in browser local storage. To access protected API routes, you can include the token in the `Authorization` header of your `axios` requests.

In this example, I showed a simple implementation of JWT authentication. In a real-world application, you would implement credential validation using a database and encrypt passwords using a library like `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Identity`.

In this case, you can create a protected route on both the frontend (using React) and backend (using C# with ASP.NET Core Web API).

**Backend (C# with ASP.NET Core Web API)**

1. Add an `[Authorize]` attribute to your controller's action with a specific role requirement (in this case, the teacher):

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;

[ApiController]
[Route("api/[controller]")]
public class ExamController : ControllerBase
{
    [HttpPost("create")]
    [Authorize(Roles = "Teacher")]
    public IActionResult CreateExam([FromBody] ExamRequest request)
    {
        // Implementation of creating an exam
    }
}
```

Make sure your existing JWT implementation includes role claims when generating tokens. If you need to associate specific users with roles, you should implement that in your authentication logic.

**Frontend (React)**

1. Create a higher-order component (HOC) to wrap protected components and check the user role:

```javascript
import React from 'react';
import { Redirect } from 'react-router-dom';

const withRoleProtection = (Component, requiredRole) => {
  return (props) => {
    const user = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('user'));

    if (!user || user.role !== requiredRole) {
      return <Redirect to="/unauthorized" />;
    }

    return <Component {...props} />;
  };
};

export default withRoleProtection;
```

2. Now, wrap the component you want to protect with the `withRoleProtection` higher-order component, specifying the required role:

```javascript
import React from 'react';
import withRoleProtection from './withRoleProtection';

function CreateExamPage() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Create an exam</h2>
      {/* Your form to create an exam */}
    </div>
  );
}

export default withRoleProtection(CreateExamPage, 'Teacher');
```

This will ensure that only users with the "Teacher" role can access the `CreateExamPage` component. If a user without the "Teacher" role tries to access the page, they will be redirected to the "/unauthorized" route.

**Note**: This solution relies on the user information in local storage, which can be manipulated by the user. The frontend check is more for the user experience while the backend check provides real security. Make sure your server-side authentication and authorization are correctly implemented to prevent unauthorized access to protected endpoints.
